Next-generation sequencing (NGS) is one of the greatest achievements of the modern era. Beyond genome sequencing from known organisms, it allowed discovery of novel viruses responsible for unknown human diseases (
 Palacios 
  et al., 2008
 ), and tracking of outbreaks and pandemics such as influenza (
 Baillie 
  et al., 2012
 ) to understand their emergence and transmission profiles (
 Leung 
  et al., 2014
 ; 
 Isakov 
  et al., 2015
 ).
